result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both Operating w/ PAC (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)] and OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)]. The defendant was found guilty of Operating w/ PAC (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)] and the other charge, OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)] was dismissed by the court.

  • Kyle J. Frazier was found guilty of Operating w/ PAC (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(b).
  • Kyle J. Frazier was found guilty of Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
District Attorney Daniel S. Diehn appeared on behalf of the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Ritland.  Defendant plead guilty to Count 2 and Count 4 in 16CM139 and count 1 in 16CM175.  OWI dismissed by operation of law.  Remaining counts in those cases dismissed but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court advised the defendant of the charge and possible penalties of the counts the defendant plead to.  He understood.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  He understood.  Prior conviction confirmed by the court with the defendant and Attorney Ritland.   Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Find guilty of PAC 2nd contrary to 346.63(1)(b), Resist/obstruct contrary to 946.41(1) and misdemeanor bail jumping contrary to 946.49(1)(a).    Joint recommendation for:  in 16CM139, PAC 2nd - 20 days jail, $1,555.00 fine and costs.  14 month revocation of driver's license and IID requirement.  Alcohol assessment and driver's safety plan.  Count 4 obstruct.  5 days jail, consecutive to count 2.  In 16CM175, 5 days jail, consecutive to 16CM139.  Defense requesting 2 weeks to report to jail.  Pay fine @ $50.00 per month.  

Court ordered:  in 16CM139, PAC 2nd - 20 days jail, starting on or before 5/25 at 6:00 pm.  Stayed until then on condition he not possess or consume alcohol.  stay lifted immediately if apprehended in the interim.  $1,555.00 fine and costs.  14 month revocation of driver's license and IID requirement.  Alcohol assessment and driver's safety plan.  Count 4 obstruct.  5 days jail, consecutive to count 2.  CC.  In 16CM175, 5 days jail, consecutive to 16CM139.  CC.  Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.  Pay @ 50/mo starting 6/1.  (BJ & Obstruct)  Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.  (PAC)  Failure to pay any part of the fine and court costs will result in 30 days jail.

Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.
